  "prompt": "In Tagalog, what are the rules for using Nang and Ng?",
  "response": "In Tagalog, \"nang\" and \"ng\" are both important particles that serve different grammatical functions. Here are the rules for using them:\n\n### Ng\n1. **Genitive Marker**: \"Ng\" is used to indicate possession or relationship, similar to the English \"of.\"\n   - Example: \"Bahay ng guro\" (House of the teacher).\n\n2. **Direct Object Marker**: It is used to mark the direct object of a verb.\n   - Example: \"Kumain ng mansanas\" (Ate an apple).\n\n3. **Adjective-Noun Connection**: It connects adjectives to nouns.\n   - Example: \"Magandang bahay ng guro\" (The beautiful house of the teacher).\n\n### Nang\n1. **Adverbial Marker**: \"Nang\" is often used to indicate manner, time, or reason, similar to \"when\" or \"how\" in English.\n   - Example: \"Kumanta siya nang maganda\" (She sang beautifully).\n\n2. **Connecting Clauses**: It connects clauses, particularly subordinate clauses.\n   - Example: \"Natutulog siya nang siya ay nag-aaral\" (He was sleeping when he was studying).\n\n3. **Indicating Duration or Extent**: It can also indicate the extent of time or degree.\n   - Example: \"Nang ilang taon\" (For several years).\n\n### Summary\n- Use **\"ng\"** for possession, direct objects, and adjective-noun relationships.\n- Use **\"nang\"** for adverbial connections, to link clauses, and to indicate duration or extent.\n\nUnderstanding the context of each sentence will help determine whether to use \"nang\" or \"ng.\"",
